---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeTabs from '../../components/CodeTabs.astro';
import FieldLoopDemo from '../../components/FieldLoopDemo.astro';
import { MANUAL_FORCES } from '@field-ui/core';

// Getting started — install + a 60-second quickstart for every entry point + the
// mental model. Snippets live as consts so Astro renders angle-brackets and braces
// as literal escaped text.

const htmlSnippet = `<!-- 1. register the element -->
<` + `script type="module">
  import '@field-ui/elements';
</` + `script>

<!-- 2. drop the field + mark any element as a body -->
<field-root accent="#4da3ff"></field-root>

<a data-body="attract" data-strength="0.9" data-range="320" data-feedback>
  pull me
</a>`;

const reactSnippet = `import { FieldField } from '@field-ui/react';

export function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <FieldField accent="#4da3ff" onReady={(field) => field.scan()} />
      <a data-body="attract" data-strength="0.9" data-range="320" data-feedback>
        pull me
      </a>
    </>
  );
}`;

const coreSnippet = `import { FieldField } from '@field-ui/vanilla';

// builds + manages a fixed full-viewport canvas, starts the engine
const field = new FieldField({ accent: '#4da3ff' });

// any [data-body] element on the page becomes a force the field reacts to.
// after adding bodies to the DOM, rescan:
field.scan();`;
---

<DocsLayout
  title="field-ui — Developer docs"
  description="Install field-ui and get a reciprocal field reacting to your elements in under a minute — for plain HTML, React, or your own canvas. A renderer-agnostic core (zero runtime deps) with a platform layer for DOM participation."
>
  <header class="docs-hero">
    <p class="kicker">Getting started</p>
    <h1>Build with <span class="accent">field-ui</span>.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      A platform-native relational field runtime for the DOM — framework-agnostic, with a
      renderer-agnostic core. Get a field reacting to your elements in under a minute.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <p>
      Pick the entry point that matches your stack. The core engine has zero runtime
      dependencies; the adapters wrap it.
    </p>
    <div class="pkg-grid">
      <div class="pkg">
        <code class="install" data-copy="npm i @field-ui/elements">npm i @field-ui/elements</code>
        <span>the <code>&lt;field-root&gt;</code> web component — drops into any framework or plain HTML</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pkg">
        <code class="install" data-copy="npm i @field-ui/react">npm i @field-ui/react</code>
        <span>the <code>&lt;FieldField&gt;</code> React component + <code>useFieldField</code> hook</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pkg">
        <code class="install" data-copy="npm i @field-ui/vanilla">npm i @field-ui/vanilla</code>
        <span>the framework-free <code>FieldField</code> class + <code>mountField()</code> for plain TypeScript</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pkg">
        <code class="install" data-copy="npm i @field-ui/core">npm i @field-ui/core</code>
        <span>the engine itself — when you own the canvas</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Quick start</h2>
    <p>
      The same field, three ways — pick the tab that matches your stack. Each snippet is the
      whole setup: register the field, then mark an element as a body. Hit <b>Copy</b> and paste.
    </p>
    <CodeTabs
      variants={[
        { label: 'Web component', lang: 'html', code: htmlSnippet },
        { label: 'React', lang: 'tsx', code: reactSnippet },
        { label: 'Vanilla', lang: 'ts', code: coreSnippet },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="callout">
      <b>The field reacts to the page.</b> A field root creates a shared field context: the platform
      layer discovers and measures every <code>[data-body]</code> element each frame, the core
      computes the field, and feedback returns density to the DOM as CSS variables and events. A
      canvas renders the visible field behind your content — so any layout change <em>is</em> a change
      to the force geometry. After you add or remove bodies, call <code>field.scan()</code>.
    </div>

    <p class="see-it">
      See it before you build it. These are semantic elements with <code>data-body</code> and a supplied
      metric; <code>applyRecipe()</code> writes that metric back as <code>--field-*</code>, and the CSS
      reads it. No canvas widget — the data-attribute contract, running.
    </p>
    <FieldLoopDemo
      token="attract"
      recipe="priority-well"
      metric="priority"
      items={[
        { text: 'Ship the runtime', value: 0.9 },
        { text: 'Write the guide', value: 0.5 },
        { text: 'Tidy the changelog', value: 0.2 },
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>The mental model</h2>
    <ul class="model">
      <li>
        <b>Bodies.</b> Any element with <code>data-body="&lt;force&gt; &lt;force&gt;…"</code>
        becomes a force (forces compose). Tune it with <code>data-strength</code>,
        <code>data-range</code>, <code>data-color</code>, and a condition gate
        <code>data-when</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>Platform.</b> <code>@field-ui/platform</code> binds bodies to the DOM — measurement,
        state, feedback, relationships, visual bindings, and overlays, on a six-phase scheduler
        (<code>discover → read → compute → state → write → render</code>).
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>Core &amp; render surfaces.</b> <code>field-ui</code> (the core) computes the field
        (renderer-agnostic) over one shared, conserved context. Canvas, SVG overlays, and DOM
        feedback are render surfaces that reveal it — nothing is created from nothing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <b>Reciprocity.</b> Add <code>data-feedback</code> and the field writes the gathered density
        back into your element as <code>--field-density</code> (compact <code>--d</code> /
        <code>--forces-density</code> aliases too) — drive weight, glow, and scale from it.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec next">
    <h2>Where to go next</h2>
    <div class="next-grid">
      <a class="next-card" href="/docs/concepts">
        <b>Concepts</b>
        <span>The model in depth — bodies, the shared field context, the platform layer, reciprocity.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="next-card" href="/docs/api/forces">
        <b>The {MANUAL_FORCES.length} forces</b>
        <span>The full API reference — law, attributes, and an example per force.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="next-card" href="/docs/guides/web-component">
        <b>Framework guides</b>
        <span>Web component, TypeScript, React, and the core engine — pick your entry point.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="next-card" href="/lab">
        <b>The Lab</b>
        <span>A physics detector — fire a particle into any force and verify its behavior.</span>
      </a>
      <a class="next-card" href="/design">
        <b>Design system</b>
        <span>The visual language behind the field — tokens, the force palette, type, and glyphs.</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
